HTML, or HyperText Markup Language, is the backbone of the World Wide Web. It serves as the standard markup language for creating web pages and web applications. HTML allows you to structure content on the internet, making it readable and accessible by web browsers.

HTML documents are made up of elements, which are enclosed by tags. These tags define the structure and content of a web page. For example, the <h1> tag is used to create a top-level heading, while the <p> tag is used for paragraphs of text.

With HTML, you can include various types of content such as text, images, links, forms, and multimedia. It provides the foundation for adding text formatting, hyperlinks, lists, and much more to your web pages.

Learning HTML is the first step toward becoming a web developer or designer. It's an essential skill for anyone interested in creating and publishing content on the internet. Whether you're building a personal website, a blog, an e-commerce site, or a complex web application, HTML is the language that allows you to bring your ideas to life on the web.

As you delve into the world of HTML, you'll discover its powerful capabilities for creating interactive and visually appealing web experiences. Whether you're a beginner or an experienced developer, HTML remains at the core of modern web development, and mastering it is a valuable skill in today's digital age.